INSERT INTO `ipqu_posts` VALUES (257, 1, '2018-05-31 14:39:12', '2018-05-31 14:39:12', '<p id=\"4f60\" class=\"graf graf--p graf-after--h3\">You cannot have missed the furious investment efforts into the different type of intelligent personal assistants that intend to <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://www.today.com/home/best-amazon-alexa-skills-echo-dot-show-t115489\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\" data-href=\"https://www.today.com/home/best-amazon-alexa-skills-echo-dot-show-t115489\">simplify</a> our lives, such as Cortana, Alexa or Siri. There have been many <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://www.voicebot.ai/2017/06/29/apple-86-siri-job-openings-amazon-1000-alexa-jobs-unfilled/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\" data-href=\"https://www.voicebot.ai/2017/06/29/apple-86-siri-job-openings-amazon-1000-alexa-jobs-unfilled/\">reports</a> on how many jobs are currently unfilled with, among many others, Amazon and Apple in the field of speech tech, machine learning and the like.</p>\r\n<p id=\"3688\" class=\"graf graf--p graf-after--p\">The question arises: with 100+ jobs open, where should tech recruiters and sourcers look for talent?</p>\r\n<p id=\"f3dc\" class=\"graf graf--p graf-after--p\">At ipQuants, we love to mine large data sets to discover and quantify innovators. In this post, we will outline how mining patent data can help identifying innovative companies and individuals in the speech technology space.</p>\r\n<p id=\"a95d\" class=\"graf graf--p graf-after--p\">Obviously, we will not go through the actual patents themselves to get the high-level overview we want, because that would not be very efficient. But by clustering e.g. patents in particular tech categories, we can efficiently identify relevant patents and their respective owners and inventors.</p>\r\n<p id=\"a2b1\" class=\"graf graf--p graf-after--p\">Let’s focus on patents clustered into the speech recognition category, more specifically any patent filed with respect to the following category:</p>\r\n\r\n<figure id=\"491c\" class=\"graf graf--figure graf-after--p\">\r\n<div class=\"aspectRatioPlaceholder is-locked\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-188 size-full\" src=\"https://ipquants.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/1_D9MZxtjOCwyBVfZHibZ-_w.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"800\" height=\"85\" /></div></figure>\r\n<p id=\"4c75\" class=\"graf graf--p graf-after--figure\">The tech clustering we utilise is based on the so called Cooperative Patent Classification (CPC; we will spare you the details!). The CPC codes, such as G10L15/08, are maintained by the patent offices. At ipQuants we have re-structured these codes for our innovation insights purposes.</p>\r\n<p id=\"edd6\" class=\"graf graf--p graf-after--p\">This enables us to look at much more detailed technology clusters. Instead of just reviewing “speech technology” clusters, we will focus on Speech recognition with respect to<em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\"> speech classification or search</em>.</p>\r\n<p id=\"8676\" class=\"graf graf--p graf-after--p\">Based on such a cluster, we get the following patent publication trend for filings between year 2000 and 2016 at the top patent offices. Note that by law patents are published with a 18-month time lag, so that explains the highlighted part in the below chart.</p>\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-189 size-full\" src=\"https://ipquants.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/1_NIo2psez7g2JkpeGyn3JSQ.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1200\" height=\"800\" />\r\n\r\nYear 2000 to 2016 Patent Publication trend for the Tech Sector: <em class=\"markup--em markup--figure-em\">Speech recognition; </em>Speech classification or search\r\n<p id=\"2293\" class=\"graf graf--p graf-after--figure\">From above chart it is clear; there has been significant R&amp;D activity in this technology domain in recent years. Obviously, we would like to know which organisations and individuals are behind these numbers.</p>\r\n<p id=\"1c19\" class=\"graf graf--p graf-after--p\">Looking at the top patent filers in the last three years, we find the usual suspects among the top companies. Remember, we are just looking at a subset of filings of each of these companies. They could have many more speech tech related patents in other speech tech domains.</p>\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-190 size-full\" src=\"https://ipquants.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/1_davGuPzMgtXe5bSDbeK1yw.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"800\" height=\"533\" />\r\n<figure id=\"cd1a\" class=\"graf graf--figure graf-after--p\"><figcaption class=\"imageCaption\">Year 2014 to 2017 top 10 patent applicants for CPC G10L15/08</figcaption></figure>\r\n<p id=\"cc82\" class=\"graf graf--p graf-after--figure\">Google, Amazon and Microsoft are all expected probably. But what about <em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">Securus Technologies</em>? Never heard of them? You are probably not alone.</p>\r\n<p id=\"b773\" class=\"graf graf--p graf-after--p\">According to its website, <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://securustech.net/web/securus/about-us\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\" data-href=\"https://securustech.net/web/securus/about-us\">Securus Technologies</a> is the largest prison inmate communication provider. Still puzzled? Well, turns out that all those phone calls the inmates conduct are monitored for various reasons. One of its patents describes how it conducts <em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">automatic keyword searching</em> during inmate phone calls… Thus, the Securus inventors seem to have very relevant know-how in the field of speech tech.</p>\r\n<p id=\"b372\" class=\"graf graf--p graf-after--p\">As a talent sourcer and recruiter for one of the top tech firms, would you have considered searching for speech technology talent at a prison security provider, such as Securus Technologies?</p>\r\n<p id=\"5baa\" class=\"graf graf--p graf-after--p graf--trailing\">Above is just one of many examples on how focusing on quantifying innovators and looking at the statistics for a particular technology field, can lead to unexpected and highly valuable insights.</p>', 'Finding Tech Talent', 'You cannot have missed the furious investment efforts into the different type of intelligent personal assistants that intend...', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '187-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-05-31 14:39:12', '2018-05-31 14:39:12', '', 187, 'https://ipquants.com/187-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `ipqu_posts` VALUES (259, 2, '2018-06-08 06:20:37', '2018-06-08 06:20:37', '<h1>EPO Board of Appeal Statistics</h1>\r\n<h2>Should you submit an Opposition appeal or not? Yes or no?</h2>\r\nYou want to be able to properly advise your company or client, but what do you base your advice on? Start with European Patent Office (EPO) Boards of Appeal (BOA) decisions. A lot more than historical records, they’re vital sources of strategic insight and clues about which direction you should advise your company or client to go.\r\n\r\nipQuants’ Boards of Appeal Module (BOAM) enables you to dive deeply into more than 20,000 BOA decisions to learn about outcomes and trends, then analyze the percentages and your options. You can evaluate hundreds of scenarios using BOAM search and report filtering options, such as:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Which appeal outcome is most likely if you have an Art. 123(2) EPC mater before a particular Board?</li>\r\n 	<li>Is it different if you have a case of appeal following examination vs opposition?</li>\r\n 	<li>Which T, J, or G decision is the selected Board citing the most?</li>\r\n 	<li>How does it change in view of a particular appeal outcome or legal provision?</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Board of Appeal Insights', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '116-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-06-08 06:20:37', '2018-06-08 06:20:37', '', 116, 'https://ipquants.com/116-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `ipqu_posts` VALUES (262, 2, '2018-08-30 14:20:42', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '<strong>Data-Driven Legal Decision Making</strong>\r\n\r\nAfter a Patent Examiner has refused to accept your fabulous argument and rejected your client’s patent application, your next step is advising your client. What advice will you deliver? Will you recommend filing an appeal or accepting the Examiner’s decision?\r\n\r\n<strong>To Appeal or Not to Appeal? </strong>\r\n\r\nWe have all been there as attorneys, managing a pro-and-con evaluation that far-too-often ends with a hunch. Wouldn’t you love instead to share some data to support your counsel? A piece of objective data that substantiates the wisdom to proceed, and helps you avoid delivering advice like this:\r\n\r\n<em>“We will apply the same arguments we made during examination, but this time the outcome will be different. The Appeal Board will get it. Trust us.”</em>\r\n\r\nOften times, appeal recommendations are based on an assumption or belief that, because they are more experienced, Board Members will recognize the merits of your arguments that were obviously and unfortunately overlooked the first time. Would you feel as confident if you had to wager your money rather than your client’s on the outcome?\r\n\r\n<strong>Do Appeal Boards Really See Things Differently? </strong>\r\n\r\nAn important part of the appeal recommendation process is to provide the client with an estimate of the likelihood of success. A common starting point is to survey peers and partners. You could ask them about their experience under these circumstances. If you’re lucky to chat with enough colleagues and speak with a senior partner if available, you may be able to gather a tiny historical sample. It may require a couple of hours, after which you may or may not be happy with the consensus—if indeed there was any.\r\n\r\nThe client awaits your counsel. Wouldn’t it be nice to deliver advice more grounded in objectivity than opinion? What if you could add some objectivity by accessing some data supporting your position? Something you could use to substantiate that the likelihood the Appeal Boards will see things differently than the Examining Division is in fact rather high. We’re sure it would be well received because it’s probably one of your clients more important cases.\r\n\r\nSo, you could conduct your office survey or just tell your client the following:\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>In 48.5% of all EPO Appeals during examination, the Appeal Boards eventually ruled in favor of the Applicant.</li>\r\n 	<li>In 61.7% of cases relating to Art 123(2), the Appeal Boards ruled to either remit the case for grant or instructed the Examining Division to continue the examination procedure.</li>\r\n 	<li>Overall, the Appeal Board 3.2.03 has ruled in the Applicant’s favor in 66.2% of Examination Appeal cases.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you were facing the possibility of appearing before the Appeal Boards, wouldn’t it be valuable and almost comforting to be able to access and analyze the specific board’s historical decisions and track record?\r\n\r\nIt would certainly be more worthwhile and efficient than ambling through the office conducting a thoroughly unscientific survey about the Board’s behavior. Plus, you’d be able to help your client prepare a business case to internally justify the possibly unplanned appeal costs. Appeals are not inexpensive options; your clients would undoubtedly appreciate advice combining both legal perspective and business reality.\r\n\r\n<strong>Don’t Guess. Know.</strong>\r\n\r\nAssuming your client decides to accept your thoughtful (and objectively reasoned) recommendation to file an Appeal, now you have to prepare the case. Wouldn’t it be great to know how the specific Appeal Board has ruled in the past in similar cases? Of course it would.\r\n\r\nLet’s consider a case in which we have an Art 123(2) EPC matter before the Appeal Board 3.2.03. This chart visualizes that Board’s timeline for past decisions involving at least Article 123(2) EPC.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://ipquants.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/3.2.03_BoA_BlogJune.svg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-285 aligncenter\" src=\"https://ipquants.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/3.2.03_BoA_BlogJune.svg\" alt=\"\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWe can drill down to a particular year, such as the 15 cases decided in 2017. We can then study the actual decisions to gain insights into the thought processes of this Board. Moreover, we could instantly retrieve the decisions this Board cited when evaluating matters relating to Art. 123(2) EPC.\r\n\r\nQuantifying the Appeals Boards data in this matter creates an objectively clear map of individual Boards and their historic records. Rather than conducting random or ad hoc case law research in preparation for drafting Grounds of Appeal or the Oral Proceedings, you could significantly increase your productivity by focusing your preparation work. Most importantly, you would end up standing in front of the Board as absolutely prepared as possible, a state your client expects.\r\n\r\nYou only get one chance to defend your case before the relevant Board. ipQuants will ensure that your chance of a positive outcome is tilted as much in your favor as possible.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Data-Driven Legal Decision Making', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2018-08-30 14:20:42', '2018-08-30 14:20:42', '', 0, 'https://ipquants.com/?p=262', 0, 'post', '', 0);
