han opinion? What if you could add some objectivity by accessing some data supporting your position? Something you could use to substantiate that the likelihood the Appeal Boards will see things differently than the Examining Division is in fact rather high. We’re sure it would be well received because it’s probably one of your clients more important cases.\r\n\r\nSo, you could conduct your office survey or just tell your client the following:\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>In 48.5% of all EPO Appeals during examination, the Appeal Boards eventually ruled in favor of the Applicant.</li>\r\n 	<li>In 61.7% of cases relating to Art 123(2), the Appeal Boards ruled to either remit the case for grant or instructed the Examining Division to continue the examination procedure.</li>\r\n 	<li>Overall, the Appeal Board 3.2.03 has ruled in the Applicant’s favor in 68.8% of Examination Appeal cases.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nIf you were facing the possibility of appearing before the Appeal Boards, wouldn’t it be valuable and almost comforting to be able to access and analyze the specific board’s historical decisions and track record?\r\n\r\nIt would certainly be more worthwhile and efficient than ambling through the office conducting a thoroughly unscientific survey about the Board’s behavior. Plus, you’d be able to help your client prepare a business case to internally justify the possibly unplanned appeal costs. Appeals are not inexpensive options; your clients would undoubtedly appreciate advice combining both legal perspective and business reality.\r\n\r\n<strong>Don’t Guess. Know.</strong>\r\n\r\nAssuming your client decides to accept your thoughtful (and objectively reasoned) recommendation to file an Appeal, now you have to prepare the case. Wouldn’t it be great to know how the specific Appeal Board has ruled in the past in similar cases? Of course it would. However, you may not have or want to invest an entire month (or two) to gather such insights.\r\n\r\nLet’s consider a case in which we have an Art 123(2) EPC matter before the Appeal Board 3.2.03. This chart visualizes that Board’s timeline for past decisions involving at least Article 123(2) EPC.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-268 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://ipquants.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/BlogPost_BoA-150x150.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWe can drill down to a particular year, such as the 17 cases decided in 2017. We can then study the actual decisions to gain insights into the thought processes of this Board. Moreover, we could instantly retrieve the decisions this Board cited when evaluating matters relating to Art. 123(2) EPC.\r\n\r\nQuantifying the Appeals Boards data in this matter creates an objectively clear map of individual Boards and their historic records. Rather than conducting random or ad hoc case law research in preparation for drafting Grounds of Appeal or the Oral Proceedings, you could significantly increase your productivity by focusing your preparation work. Most importantly, you would end up standing in front of the Board as absolutely prepared as possible, a state your client expects.\r\n\r\nYou only get one chance to defend this case before the relevant Board. ipQuants will ensure that your chance of a positive outcome is tilted as much in your favor as possible.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Using Data to Advise Clients about EPO Appeal Boards', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '262-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-06-22 13:50:02', '2018-06-22 13:50:02', '', 262, 'https://ipquants.com/262-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
